ExxonMobil exits Torrance as PBF Energy assumes ownership and operation of refinery








        Torrance Mayor Pat Furey, center, with new Torrance Refining Company executives Jeff Dill and PBF Western Region President, CEO Tom Nimbley, left, and Steve Steach, Refinery Manager, right. The transition ceremony marked the takeover of the ExxonMobil plant in Torrance by the new Torrance Refining Company. July 1, 2016. (Brad Graverson / Staff Photographer)
        










  By
  Nick Green, Daily Breeze




                                            Posted: 
                                        07/01/16, 5:55 PM PDT
|
Updated: on 07/01/2016

# Comments










                PBF CEO Tom Nimbley  spoke at the transition ceremony for the new Torrance Refining Company as it takes over the ExxonMobil plant in Torrance. July 1, 2016. (Brad Graverson / Staff Photographer)
                







PBF Energy officially assumed ownership Friday of the ExxonMobil Torrance Refinery, bringing an end to the oil giant’s catastrophic final 15 months in charge of the aging plant after a February 2015 explosion shattered the confidence of residents in the company’s ability to operate it safely. PBF unveiled new white-and-blue signs at a brief ribbon-cutting ceremony Friday, while pledging to operate the plant, now called the Torrance Refining Co. Refinery, in a safe, reliable and environmentally responsible manner. 



“I really have empathy for the people of Torrance,” said CEO and Chairman Tom Nimbley. “It’s been a difficult 18 months for them. Torrance was always viewed as the best refinery in the state. It’s our intention to get it back to that level.”The pledge of reliability was put to the test early when company and city officials struggled to remove a securely fastened covering to unveil the sign; a burly worker eventually gave it the requisite hard tug to finish the job.Assemblyman David Hadley put the event in context in a statement read by former Councilman Tom Brewer, now a member of the Republican’s district staff.



“Let’s be honest about this,” he said. “This is not a celebration; it’s a transition. This is not a victory lap; it’s a chance for a new beginning here in Torrance and we’re cheering you on to succeed.“Your predecessor lost significant confidence and goodwill in the community in recent years,” Hadley’s statement said. “It’s sad to say this, but that’s true. We want you to succeed and we’ll cheer you on, but we want you first and foremost to protect the safety of the people in the South Bay.”ExxonMobil’s safety record since the blast frightened many members of the community and prompted the formation of no fewer than three grass-roots groups that are demanding safety improvements.



Both state and federal investigators have blamed ExxonMobil for the blast, including citing a deliberate decision not to fix equipment the company knew could cause a life-threatening explosion.The state has fined the company more than $500,000, while the U.S. Chemical Safety Board issued subpoenas to the company in an effort to uncover more information in the blast’s wake.ExxonMobil has appealed the fine and numerous state citations, while also ignoring some CSB subpoenas, much to the anger of politicians like Rep. Ted Lieu, D-Manhattan Beach, a former Torrance City Council member.




Advertisement




The South Coast Air Quality Management District also is conducting a study to determine whether an alternative to extremely toxic modified hydrofluoric acid is viable for use at the refinery. The acid forms a toxic ground-hugging gas at room temperature that could kill thousands in the densely populated area during an accidental release.CSB officials have said a catastrophic release of the acid was only averted during the explosion when debris hit scaffolding erected for future maintenance around a large vessel containing MHF.



ExxonMobil has only reluctantly communicated with city residents since the explosion, largely when compelled to by government officials holding public hearings on the explosion.No ExxonMobil official played a formal role in Friday’s ribbon-cutting, although a member of its public relations staff was on hand to take photos.Public confidence was further eroded by a series of relatively minor accidents since the 1.7-magnitude blast that literally rocked the city, showered neighborhoods with industrial debris and increased gas pump prices.



The incidents included an accidental release of highly toxic modified hydrofluoric acid and, just last week, the collapse of a 300-ton crane. PBF already has taken steps to improve community outreach.Workers Friday were seen tending to the unkempt landscaping around the refinery. That was a source of complaints by community leaders before last year’s explosion convinced many they had bigger problems to deal with at the plant than aesthetics.PBF has also used delays in the ownership transfer — originally scheduled to close in the first quarter — to reach out to a variety of community organizations, including “a lot of groups our predecessor did not have a dialogue with,” said Jeffrey Dill, president of PBF Energy Western Region LLC.



“Everything falls into place when the refinery is running reliably, people are kept safe, we are a good member of the community, and that’s the place we want to be,” Dill said.In addition, PBF has committed to an independent third-party review of the refinery to see if any improvements are recommended and plans to extend an automated monitoring system of the MHF unit to the city Fire Department, Dill said. That monitoring system is already tied in to equipment at the AQMD.With the $537.5 million purchase of the 155,000-barrel-per-day refinery that was announced last year, PBF increases its refining capacity to about 900,000 barrels of crude a day, making it North America’s fourth-largest independent refiner.



In addition to the 750-acre north Torrance refinery, PBF has acquired a network of pipelines, storage facilities and distribution terminals.Those pipelines send crude oil from the ports of Long Beach and Los Angeles to the refinery, while jet fuel is sent from the refinery to Los Angeles International Airport.PBF also acquired a 171-mile crude gathering and transportation system, which delivers San Joaquin Valley crude oil directly from the oil field to the refinery.Dill said PBF plans further investment to improve the refinery. Next year a major maintenance project is planned to overhaul the half of the refinery that wasn’t shut down by the explosion.



PBF stock closed Friday at $24.06 on the New York Stock Exchange, up 28 cents.





